The point-slope form of the equation of a line is $y-y_1=m(x-x_1),$ where $(x_1,y_1)$ is a point on the line.  We substitute $m=\frac12,$ $x_1=2,$ and $y_1=-3$ to find  \[y-(-3)=\frac12(x-2).\] Simplifying the right side gives $\frac12x-1,$ so \[y+3=\frac12x-1.\] Subtracting 3 from both sides gives $y=\frac12x-4.$  The $y$-intercept occurs when $x=0,$ so $y=\frac12(0)-4=\boxed{-4}.$ [asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

